name: Gabrielle Schaffner
bio:
Ceramic artist, cooker, birder, sometimes reader, assistant to the Explorer.
Next show/sale: online, a special offering of just pasta boards 10/1

social_posts.post_text: Rummaging through my sketchbook for painting inspiration this morning. 🖤🕊️🐦🏺

Funny how 4pm feels like the middle of the night these days. 

I’m in my familiar corner, painting away, trying to get the kiln filled. 

✨💫This Sunday, @lauradavidsonbooks and I, plus our daughter, will open our studio for a small holiday sale. 🌟✨

I’ll post more about it tomorrow, and I’ll be sending an email out to my mailing list with all the details. You can sign up for my mailing list on my website or via the link in my bio.

Espresso cups getting loaded into the bisque, a peek at @lauradavidsonbooks paintings in progress wall, and a look into the kiln, and the tree is UP 🎄

This Sunday we’re opening our studio for the first time since…since “before times.” Our daughter Michela is joining in, with cards and ornaments. 
And five other artists in our building will be open as well:
@lindahueyceramics 
@johnsdykes 
@martinberinstein 
Frank Berinstein woodworking
Susan Anderson painting

And the gallery on the first floor has Paper Clips, a show of works on paper. 

We’ll be open from 12-5pm. 

Metered Parking on A Street is free on Sundays, and we’re a short walk from South Station.

Thank you so much to everyone who came out to visit us today 🥰❤️

It was the first time we’d opened our studio to the public since before Covid-times, and the first time @lauradavidsonbooks and Michela and I all opened together in our home— and it was absolutely a joy. 

I was definitely overwhelmed by the flood of early shoppers, and amazed to send so many pots out the door. I won’t have enough work for an online shop update this week—but there are lots of pots in progress for the new year. 

Bonus—we got a tiny bit of snow tonight! ✨

Owl and flowers on my table TRYING to get me motivated to paint a last few  pots for Christmas gifts. Must. Pick. Up. Paintbrush. 😜(I know once I do I’ll get in a groove, but sometimes STARTING is just a challenge…)

Swipe to see the most perfect cup which arrived from Australia this morning—deco inspired beauty by @susanfrost feels so lux. 

And in other news—📰📣my orchid re bloomed! (thankful to @randitriant for her orchid advice and housecalls 🧑🏼‍⚕️🩺🪴).

A sweet end to the shortest day.
 
🥂to the light slowly returning ✨

I can hardly believe we’re on the cusp of Christmas!

Here’s a peek at this year’s windowsills. 
Every year @lauradavidsonbooks and Michela and I create scenes (we each get a window sill—and then there is a lot of mission creep as well…not many surfaces left!). 

Laura and I have our minis from when we were kids, our daughter has a vast collection from over the years—and there are many handmade additions. Last year L&M made me an outdoor pizza oven! (In L’s scene this year) and I am still marveling at  the tiny cookbooks L made me, copies of my favorites. The bears are enjoying coffee and toast from a set made by @bluebearvendingco! 
M’s scene is in the dollhouse L made her when she was little—it is always a wild party scene 😊

Here’s to a gentle 2023–happy new year friends 🥂

I’ve been quiet here so I’m squeezing in snippets from the last week— 
we celebrated New Year’s Eve by making culurgionis from Bitter Honey, with backup support from Pasta Grannies and YouTube, with Marcella’s tomato butter sauce. Culurgionis are Sardinia’s pasta filled with potato and cheese 💫 they are delicious and—newsflash—Laura was better at crimping than I was 🤩
The rest:
Foggy NYE day walk at the beach, a hike to a reservoir led by M, our wedding anniversary, a Christmas mug from Jamie, a spectacular hand made Christmas tree for me by Laura and Michela, 
Carla Tomasi focaccia, Neapolitan peppery almond taralli, a teeny tiny copy of Emiko’s Cinnamon and Salt by L for the mini cookbook library she made me earlier, and anniversary sunset at the beach. 

Wishing you all good things ✨

Three years ago this week we were wandering a foggy Florence, strolling a sparkling Rome, seeing one of the best shows ever of ancient Roman frescoes and pots, eating well, and basking in the beauty of it all. (I mean, there was also lost luggage and an awful bug that swept through us all but who remembers that?!)

This week here I’m moving slowly and nursing a concussion (fell on some ice and whacked my head. It’s not awful or dramatic or dire, but it is annoying. The world is so loud and bright, I hadn’t noticed before💥). 

So I am poking along, resting, percolating, moving slowly towards getting my studio in order. Or towards the idea of it . Reading— although one of Dos and Don’ts lists might have said not to🫣—but 🤷🏻‍♀️📚. 
Might clean my painting table off today 🥳

My Christmas gift artichoke from @lauradavidsonbooks is up on the wall, along with a marvelous owl that @bluebearvendingco gave us some years back. 

And I might never open that last mini panettone because I love the packaging so much. 

The gorgeous trees painting is one we’ve had for a very long time—I’m sure I’ll think of that artist after I post this. 🤔

Sat at my work table and did actual work today 🥳🥳🥳

Here’s a tumbler I made in December, along with the fresco bit that inspired it (pulled from a magazine ages ago).

A good day for nesting 🪺✨

Coffee and a biscotto for dipping (thanks Fred!), big fat snow flakes to make me happy (but not enough to be a pain) and the Via Carota cookbook recipe for Carabaccia that @domenicacooks wrote about in last week’s newsletter (it was one more thing that pushed me over the line to order the book. No regrets!). 

The soup is delicious, perfect for today. It made me think of my stepmother’s delicious French onion soup (Julia Childs) but is also completely different. That’s a poached egg hiding in there 
🍳🥣 🧅

Painting spoons, and suddenly it’s Friday evening! I’m not quite sure how that happened, but it’s nice to have gotten a little work done. 

Happy weekends, people 😘😘

Spoons in the rubble of my windowsill “side table”
Flip side, on my work table
And one last one that almost got away…
They are unfired, the colors will change a bit. 🥄🥄🥄🥄🥄🥄

Owl in a snowy tree (or maybe that’s a spring blooming tree?) on my sketchbook. 
And a peek out my studio window. Glad the rain changed over ❄️

Lots of black and white in the studio this week, although I’m thinking some of it will be finished in color transparent glaze, like the bowl in the second picture. 

Last night I dreamt I was about to interview at a local restaurant to be a pastaia (pasta maker). But in my dream I was trying to tell them, I don’t have much time, I make pottery for a job. And also, my curlugionis are a MESS. I woke up so confused. And happy to just make pots. And pasta when I want to. 😂

Not exactly pasta tonight, but filled crespelle in the works. 
Happy weekend to you 😘😘

Finally finished the large bowl I’ve been painting this week 🖤🤍. I might glaze it in that transparent green 💚✨, we’ll see. 

Happy Friday, how is it here again?!
I’m going to go roast a chicken and some veg and listen to the wind howl out there. 🌬️💨💨
Honestly not going out until it thaws on Sunday 🥶

Stay cosy, my friends ❤️

Cheers me to put flowers in unfired pots 🤩
(Just have to not forget).

I don’t know about a Superb Owl, but he is at least a sweet owl. 

🌝😘

Odds and ends, half done. 🥰

Quick, tell me your very favorite super easy dinner idea ❤️
Every week I sort of meal plan—sketch out a general idea of what to cook, and then I add a side bar of simple things in case I need a sort of escape hatch. 

But every week I pencil in “grilled cheese” or “omelettes” in that spot and can’t think of anything else. 
Pasta is our unofficial, unwritten “what to make when you can’t think of anything”…

What about you? I’m all ears!

I’m still here ☺️—but I swear, the longer you don’t post the stranger it is to finally post again. 
Here are some glimpses from the past two weeks ❤️

Life keeps tossing out road blocks and detours, so I’ve been working at a snail’s pace, but I do take comfort that even slow progress gets you somewhere in the end!

Lots of cooking time as our daughter had all four wisdom teeth out (Puddings! Purées! Thankful we seem to have moved through that phase now). 

Lots of half-hearted snow here too, but it all turns to rain—for the first time ever i don’t think I mind ☺️. 

And slowly and seem to have painted most of the assorted green ware in my studio. Just a few more and then I’ll fire and then start the cycle again!

Painting a small batch of pasta boards this week. 
The little pitcher is inspired by the fresco in 2nd picture—
[Saint Guido of Pomposa turns water into wine, witnessed by Bishop Geberardo of Ravenna (detail). Fresco, c. 1316/20, ascribed to Pietro da Rimini]

I saved it because every time I look at it I imagine my old tumbler snuck into the scene via time travel (third pic) if you squint I swear I’m right 😂

In other news, I’m taking Italian classes! You can tell because I’ve scrawled a vocabulary word on my work table 😁🫣 SCARABOCCHIANDO which means doodling/sketching. 

Thanks to everyone who responded to my Italian studies question a few months back—it was @emikodavies who introduced me to @sumisuraitaly ❤️. Exactly what I was looking for—Italian lessons which could meet me where I am, and match my interests. 
So far besides my actual lessons, I’m reading a contemporary mystery, (L’imprevedibile piano della srittrice senza nome” di Alcie Basso), listened to a podcast interview on feminism, watched an artists Ted talk and a history of spaghetti —see what I mean?! That, and tackling the intricacies of the congiuntivo tense (ouch my brain) with my awesome instructor.

Still painting but almost ready to fire (even if I’ve been saying that for weeks 🤩). 

I tried to stay loose and embrace my inner Bloomsbury on this vase 🎨 🖌️ 

And I finished up a small round of pasta boards (the backs are textured for rolling pasta textures, flip side painted so you can hang them up decoratively when not in use). Here’s hoping they don’t warp in the kiln! (I dried them so slowly, under weights, but you still never know 🫣).

This week’s non-studio project: orange marmalade!

Recipe from @rachelaliceroddy ‘s Two Kitchens 📖. 

I had a few bumps in the road but I think the end result is delicious. 
Thanks to Rachel for providing 911 DM support when I got befuddled. And to Carla for standing by just in case 💖

I also: didn’t have enough bitter oranges (filled the weight out w regular oranges which apparently have less pectin, so it’s a bit runny), ran out of sugar and walked to the store in a 🌧️🌬️❄️, then I overboiled my (too small, I really knew it 🤪) pot (what a mess 😩), but in the end… 🍊JOY! And toast!

Gorgeous bowl in the second pic is by @jgugginaceramics.

Finally! I fired a bisque and I’m in the midst of glazing. 

Also, as seen in the final blurry photo, I had an unexpected visitor. The weather is turning springy and I left the window open a few inches without putting the screen in…🕊️…and was greeted by cooing of a mourning dove when I walked in the morning. 
Do you know that sound they make when they fly? There was a lot of panicked flying, and a lot of me rushing around apologizing (🤷🏻‍♀️) while throwing windows open fast as I could. It got out pretty quickly and I was relieved to see the pair of them later (outside!). 
[text from my daughter: “See that’s why you don’t open windows ”] 🫣🐦

A few new plates ✨
I’ve been playing with greens, but still also black and white.

Honestly I made the most lackluster (it was bad) dinner last night, so I was searching for a little redemption tonight 🍝

“Pappardelle sui funghi” from @emikodavies Aquacotta, wide noodles with mushrooms. It was simple and delicious and we were all three happy. 

Followed by a double feature of @pastagrannies episodes! Back on track 🤩

Messy real life studio view ✨
I’ve just come to the end of wet clay work —I’ll trim this weekend and then a whirlwind of painting between now and the @asparagusvalleypotterytrail which is coming so fast! 

I’ll be at @jgugginaceramics studio —so many great guests this year! I simultaneously CAN’T WAIT and wish it  could be a little farther away 🫣🏺

April 29&30 with an online preview sale 4/28.

Roses on the side table. 
It’s fun to borrow some finished pots from the studio and see how they work. 
🤩🥀🤍
I think white roses are some of my favorites…they always seem so deluxe ✨

So many unpainted pots here in the studio! They are on every surface, blank canvas everywhere. 

@asparagusvalleypotterytrail is in two weeks 💕
Works in progress are stacking up. The blue of these mugs will change a bit in the firing — it will be a darker deeper blue in the end. 💙

All the wee tinies for @asparagusvalleypotterytrail ✨

I’ve been lagging and dragging for ages, since my concussion at the end of the year then a slam from the flu last week—or was it the week before? Time is a mystery. But finally: my headaches are gone! And I’m feeling better from the flu, AND I feel like I’m hitting my stride again. It’s such a relief. 

Mega thanks to  L who is picking up all the slack around here while I paint, paint, paint the pottery. 🥰
On todays painting table ✨

Everything is fired ✨

Here are a few pots from the last two kilns. Almost everything is packed up for the @asparagusvalleypotterytrail!

Green on green 🙂💚

The Asparagus Valley Pottery Sale was amazing! Thank you so much to my host @jgugginaceramics and all the potters of the @asparagusvalleypotterytrail who run such a great show—I know how much invisible work goes into it! And to @crispywan who makes the weekend at Jamie’s studio run like a well oiled machine, complete with alllllll the 🍪🍪🍪🍪❤️. 

We had the nicest visitors (and so many of them!) all weekend long. 

I am still 100% as tired as Ollie looks in front of the fire. We were so busy I didn’t take many pictures, but tucked in here is a video @mariannec2 took before we opened on Saturday. 

Also Jamie’s wall of bird pitchers, and a last view of the pond—I miss it already!

Orecchiette ✨
Perfectly imperfect! 

L and I split the batch of dough and happily rolled them out—I swear it’s the best meditative process. 

Sauced them with a fava bean pesto plus with a sort of  vignarola (artichokes, fava and peas with a little prosciutto). 

It’s so good to have some time to make pasta again!

If you ordered anything online last Friday, they should all go out tomorrow (and thank you so much🥰).

I just boxed up this sweet pasta board so it could fly across the sea to England and live with @lucyogdenceramics ❤️

I’m thinking of doing a big batch of pasta boards for a summer sale. 

If you haven’t seen my boards before, the back is textured for rolling pasta—I think porcelain works really well for it. And when you’re not using it, you can hang it up as a decorative tile!

I’ve been thinking lately about what I loved about instagram in its early days, and why I don’t post so much here these days. And, what did I even post when I posted pretty much daily?! (I know, I could look—too lazy to scroll back so far 😆). But a lot of it was just things that caught my eye in a day, nothing too thought out—so in that spirit, here are some steamed eggs cooling in my sink ✨

A delicious cake, riffed from La Vita è Dolce by @letitia_ann_clark. The recipe is really for a Cherry Almond Ricotta cake but no cherries here so I used pear. 
I loved that you put all the ingredients in a blender (I used my food processor).
It’s a keeper. 

Happy day to all the mothering people out there. 💗

Perfect Mother’s Day flowers from @crispywan & @jgugginaceramics in a Deborah Tinsman vase from the 1990s. 
The light was so funky it felt like an old filter without adding one 🤷🏻‍♀️

A large black and white plate from my last firing, and the white egret from the beach last week that I meant to share (2nd picture). 
Now I better go do my Italian homework 😘😘📖
Sneaking around the stairwells of my building for just the right patch of light 😆💕🌷

Always bring your own mugs to Airbnbs 😍.

I’m another year older (possibly wiser?) and we snuck in a mini vacation on Cape Cod this week. Wellfleet ticks all the boxes for us—big duned ocean beaches (seals bobbing in the surf!), gentler bay beaches, woods and ponds in between. And the birds! So many. It was just what we needed, and hard to come back. ❤️

We found nettles at the Wellfleet Farmers Market and brought home a big bag. Nettle ravioli! Punched out with my @qbcucina brass stamp 💕

Thanks to @julskitchen and @emikodavies — I found helpful guidance and inspiration from Emiko’s blog and from Giulia’s new cookbook Cucina Povera 💕💕💕

I haven’t been doing much that’s very photogenic lately so here’s a peek inside a favorite kitchen drawer. 
I’ll tag everyone I can, it’s crowded with good friends and excellent potters 💞

Zero complaints from me about the cool grey days we’ve been having. ✨✨

Cookbooks close at hand right now: new from @domenicacooks Everyday Italian, from @julskitchen Cucina Povera, and “old” favorite Aquacotta by @emikodavies. Plus an Agatha Christie I’ve somehow never read (They Came to Baghdad). 

It’s definitely excellent weather for cooking and reading.

I never draw on paper as an end product, if you know what I mean. I draw on clay (all the time!) or I doodle endlessly while on the phone or in a meeting…and I use my sketchbook as a way to squirrel away ideas (visual note taking I guess). 

But for my birthday last month  L. gave me inks and nibs and I’ve been having so much fun playing. In a case of perfect timing @cathycullis organized a group sketchbook weekend last week—and I filled a whole tiny book! 

✍️🖌️🖋️🖊️📖

Cheers to Monday 🥂✨

A Select spritz from @emikodavies Cinnamon and Salt. I love it because it is not sweet as an Aperol spritz 🫒🥂 
Even better, our daughter cooked dinner tonight 💖🥳

I’ve been bouncing from project to project in the studio lately, without getting my teeth sunk in (if you know what I mean?) but look! I pinched a whole batch of porcelain spoons. 

Bit by bit…
❤️

Made last week and about to make again: strawberry frozen yogurt with farmers market berries 💞

Random peony because I couldn’t resist. I promise, no peony ice cream 😜

All on a napkin @lauradavidsonbooks printed for my birthday last month, which I LOVE. 

The frozen yogurt is the simplest ice creamy thing ever. It’s just strawberries smushed up w sugar and optional splash of booze, later puréed and a cup of yogurt added. Then whirled up in an ice cream machine. Just google @davidlebovitz strawberry frozen yogurt or search his site. 

Second photo of just the little green bowl, I’m making more of these for an online sale at the end of July. 💕

I was going to say something like “get my cell ready in carbonara jail” because I made it with peas (so good! Fresh ones even!) but when I opened this app the first post I saw was from food52 and it was “carbonara” with ramen and what looked like American cheese slices. 
So…I think the cell might be full. And (@) italiansmadatfood might be busy for the night? 🤣😱🫣

Here’s a question for you. What do you like in a pasta bowl? I made these back in the 90s (I think?). Then I made some giant oversized rimmed ones but now I think they’re too much. And then I made some shallow rimless ones but…a little too small and I miss the rim. New forms in the works, but I’m all ears if you have thoughts on the Perfect Pasta Bowl shape and size. 🍝

I put handles on a small batch of mugs this afternoon—now they can hang out in a plastic bin for a few days and “bond.”
I’m easing into a new porcelain and hoping for fewer cracky handle joints. 🤞

All done and off to pick more mulberries 😂💜🟣🌳
Variations on a theme 🍝

Nine newly painted little aperitivo plates. Or maybe cookie plates? Spoon rests? Even coasters, if you like. 
I’m getting a little traction and it feels good ☺️

Are you poking around with Threads or is it a bridge too far?

🥄🥄🥄🥄🥄🥄🥄
Plus the flip sides, and a close up. 

😘😘

Its been a choppy week, but look—some mugs are painted! 

It’s funny, when you start out as a potter the focus is always on producing uniform batches—all the mugs same size and shape, etc. and so that’s how I always do it. 
It only occurred to me fairly recently that it might be nicer to have a variety. After all, I personally like a mug that holds almost 500ml (16 ounces I think) but you might like one half the size! So I made a conscious effort to assort the sizes in this batch…it felt funny when I was throwing them! 

These are unfired, the colors will change a bit as they go through their two firings. 

Happy weekend 🥂😘

Soon to be lunch plate and the old shard pile (mostly beach shards from hunting missions with my daughter). 

We’ve spent the past few days dealing with a fridge that died a sad and torturous death. So now I’m off to drag its contents out to the curb 😭. Going to be some very simple cooking here for the next week or two, as we await the arrival of a new compressor.

Gnocchetti sardi this evening—with help from L who rolls like a pro now!
This pasta board is one of my earlier ones, but there’s a new batch in the works. 

With tomatoes and basil 🍃🍅 and  meatballs (chicken and zucchini). If I see a picture of meatballs, or read about them, I am powerless to resist. 🧆

Paired with a viewing of this week’s @pastagrannies and it was such a good one. We can’t wait to try that shape!
Three black and white pasta boards  in the works. If all goes well I’ll have about a dozen of these in the next few weeks. 🍝

Yes, I do think I wish I lived in a tiny house under giant flowers this week…instead of a loft building with a four story sewage system failure. 
🚽🌧️🤢🌧️. 
Still no fridge either. 
Living the dream! 🤦🏻‍♀️😫🤣🤪 
# all the emoji

Playing around with new plate designs. This will have a clear semi-matte glaze on it when it’s done—although for some reason over black it’s often a bit shiny 🤷🏻‍♀️

My studio is a mess but here, behold: I got a grown up chair! After twenty years of working on the worst hard folding ikea chair I took the leap (under strict orders from my OT/hand therapist😂). It’s actually REALLY nice to have support and arm rests. 

Extra points to @hilary_llaww who nearly got me over the grown up chair finish line a little while ago. At last!!

Three more mugs ☕️ 
Bit by bit. 

Made it to the end of the week, and we have a refrigerator (hallelujah!!) but still down one bathroom (currently in soon to be demolished limbo). 

I hope you’re easing into an excellent weekend ❤️

When you get your kiln stacked full to the tip top and find two more pieces 😬

(I did rejigger for the third time and fit them in).

Cherry, ricotta, olive oil almond cake from Letitia Clark’s La Vita è Dolce.  Magical recipe because you just whizz everything but the cherries in the food processor.  I skipped the almonds on top because the daughter would not approve. Super delicious and easy…
Happy to catch the cherries while they’re still in season here (although I’ve made it with other fruit too). 

@lauradavidsonbooks made me the ☕️ napkin last time she printed 🥰🥰🥰

I’ll link the recipe in stories but you can google it and find it on @letitia_ann_clark’s website .

I fit one last spoon in that bisque and then we took off for a beach morning. 

I’d forgotten just how beautiful Plum Island (about 45 minutes north of Boston) is. There were hundreds and hundreds of swallows gathering to start their migration. Not pictured, all the egrets and sandpipers and other gorgeous birds—or the big sea star ⭐️ that L spotted in the rocky crag of a tide pool.

A table full of bisqueware than needs a good wash and some glazing. Here are a few pictures then a shaky video peek at the whole table full 🥰

We’re still juggling flood damage and they demolished our bathroom today (surreal to see chunks of your home carted away in a million trash bags) so I am HOPING to get the glaze kiln firing soon but, you know. 🐌🤹🏻‍♀️

Its been too hot—and our lives have been way too hectic—to get my kiln fired. It’s waiting patiently and I’m just painting more pots. 
I’m still playing with the ink and nibs I got for my birthday last spring, then noodling that onto pots in its way. 
And somehow it’s the weekend again, already! 🥂

Bottom up! (You can see them right side up if you ⬅️⬅️⬅️)

Drawing on the bottoms of my pots is something I started doing 30 years ago, when I worked in earthenware. It still feels like a sweet hidden gift to the pots’ new owners, and also like a secret doodle pad for me to play on. ✍️

I am juggling what feels like 10,000 different tasks right now but I could NOT resist making our lunch from @emikodavies new book Gohan, Everyday Japanese Cooking. 
Plus I got to test one of my new bowls 😉

We had Nasu Dengaku/Miso Eggplant, which is the first Japanese dish of Emiko’s I cooked a while back when she posted it (it’s a regular lunch favorite for us) and what should have been Green Beans with Sesame Dressing/Imen No Gomaae (when I pulled out the blanched green beans I thought I had, they burned out to be asparagus 🙂🙃)—so delicious!! And just shredded carrot salad for fresh crunch. 

I can’t wait to spend more time with this book—Japanese food is a definite runner up for favorite foods after Italian, and it’s been such a pleasure to learn how to cook some of it. 

Ok, back to taking photos for two upcoming shop updates, making new pots for Fort Point Open Studios, and finding a contractor to rebuild our bathroom. I hope you’re having a good weekend! 😘😘😘

#gohanthecookbook

🥳🥳🥳
I’m finally scheduling a shop update for my website! 

This Saturday at noon Boston time (otherwise known as EST) my website shop will update with a varied group of pots. 

I’m editing photos in the next few days and I’ll post bits here—I aim to have a full preview in the slide show on the shop page by Thursday evening. Link in my bio.

Then in about another week I’m planning a separate sale for just pasta boards—I’ll have about ten available. 

I will send emails to my list as a reminder as well. If you’d like to get emails just click the top banner on my website (or use the link in bio). 

😘😘

Okay!  Things are going my way today, it seems 🤩. My website it all loaded for Saturday’s shop update (noon on 9/23 EST). 

There’s a preview slide show on my shop page (I really wish @squarespace would roll out a real sales preview option). Link in bio to have a peek 🕵🏻‍♀️🥰

Other best news of my day was my jury duty got cancelled! 🥳🎉 Riding high. Might need to go get a lottery ticket 😂. Maybe we’ll even secure a contractor to rebuild our bathroom! 

Happy weekend people! 🥂✨
If you have questions about my sale feel free to ask or DM me.

📦📦📦 
Every one of those 63 pot is boxed and off to live its new life—hooray ! Thanks to everyone who shopped—and those of you who tried and were thwarted (sorry!). And to the best UPS man in the world who picks them up from my studio door! Now I get to get back to my painting table and make more!

This tiny little wall tile is something I’m playing with. I like how it turned out and I think I’ll make more later this fall 💕

And in case you’re curious about the blurry moka pot painting in the background it’s one of Laura’s from years ago—I popped it in the last picture.

Twelve new pasta boards are tucked into my website shop, all set to show up on Sunday Boston time at noon (EST).

We’ve been home nearly a month but I’m still finding myself in a reentry limbo. 

Maybe because we were in Italy for a sweet chunk of time, or because we came home to plunge into home reconstruction (finally rebuilding after last summer’s flood), and the funny feeling of returning just in time to jump into the holidays. 

And then of course the weight of the state of the world 🌎🔥💔. 

As much as I missed my studio I haven’t touched clay yet—still thinking and brewing I think. And poking through photos and sketches and notes from our trip. Soon though. 

In the spirit of all that, first pic is the corner of my studio you already know well, the rest are one last batch from last month in Italia.

I love the quiet of the between holidays week, and getting some time to enjoy our decorations…and the cookies too 😆. 

If you’ve been around here for a while you’ll know that every year we each take a windowsill and create a scene for the holidays, using the miniatures we’ve had from childhood, or the ones we’ve picked up (or made, or been gifted) over the years. 

You can see a video of @lauradavidsonbooks scene over on her page—and I’ll have to share some of M’s in my stories. Hers are always a raucous dollhouse party! 

This year my bear family is running a pizzeria (L made me the pizza oven a few years ago, with mini stone foraging support from M). 

I hope you’re enjoying a quiet and restorative week too ✨
